\begin_layout Subsection
Finding transcription factor binding sites
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We looked at a popular and open-source algorithm called MACS (Model-based
 analysis of ChIP-seq).
 We did a source-code study of MACS to improve our understanding of the
 code and discuss the major features of the code in our appendix.
 A brief overview for understanding the peak calling methodology is as follows.
 To find the potential binding sites from the data, MACS calculates the
 distribution of reads in the background that are not associated with any
 transcription factor binding.
 MACS uses a Poisson distribution to model the expected number of in the
 scanning window given the total number of reads and the whole genome size.
 Then peaks are identified as the likelihood of receiving a large number
 of reads in our scan window compared with the background.
 The resulting output is a list of high confidence ChIP-seq peaks that represent
 potential transcription factor binding sites.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, the statistical problem that peak finders face is a classic
 problem: they must be sensitive enough to find significant instances, and
 avoid Type I errors, but it must also be discrimitive enough to avoid false
 positives, or Type II errors.
 MACS has been shown to have wide popularity and it shows a good ability
 to identify peaks.
 But the methods that have been used for comparing experiments have basically
 reduced to finding overlaps of peaks from individual experiments, and calling
 non-overlapping peaks unique.
 We wanted to evaluate the peaks on the basis of whether they are have significa
nt different values ChIP-seq differences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Comparison of ChIP experiments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compare the results of chromatin immunoprecipitation for transcription
 factor binding sites, a general assessment looks at the overlapping peaks
 (peak-centric approach) or the overlapping target-genes (gene-centric approach)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "odom_tissue-specific_2007"

\end_inset

.
 Using microarray technology, the gene-centric approach was important because
 the microarrays were printed with oligonucleotides corresponding to genes.
 This enabled microarray gene expression experiments to detect mRNA expression
 levels, and so a gene to gene comparison was a clear discriminator.
 Using chromatin immunoprecipitation microarrays (ChIP-chip) the microarrays
 would be printed with oligonucleotides upstream of the target genes in
 order to detect the transcription factors that are the most likely regulators.
 The peak-centric approach was first started using high-density oligonucleotide
 arrays 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "odom_tissue-specific_2007"

\end_inset

 which gives higher resolution and therefore allows detection of narrower
 transcription factor binding site peaks.
 Using the peak-centric approach, overlapping peaks can be detected directly,
 and the target gene is not necessarily inferred, which has advantages for
 comparing the sequence similarity.
 Nevertheless, both approaches have advantages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Identifying differences in transcription factor occupancy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Methods for identifying differences in ChIP-seq data have been mostly demonstrat
ed as differences in overlapping peaks.
 MACS can identify differential binding sites by using setup where one experimen
t is used as control and another as a treatment.
 Therefore, the background is estimated from the local background that contains
 a potential binding site from the other experiment, and the peak caller
 has to obtain a p-value that justifies with high probability a difference.
 Therefore the argument that the peaks are different are according to the
 estimation of the Poisson rate that is highly different from the background.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One approach for incorporating replicate experiments into MACS is to concatenate
 all reads from replicates into one large file, however this is unusual
 for an experimental design point of view.
 Pooling reads is useful for some designs but it does not necessarily tell
 us about reproducability.
 Replicates have been shown to be important in measuring the reproducability
 of high-throughput experiments and many experimental designs have been
 considered for replicates including loop design and empirical Bayes smoothing
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "smyth_linear_2004"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wit_statistics_2004"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another method for finding differential peaks is MANorm which uses a linear
 model to correct for bias that may exist for differences in the reads from
 overlapping peaks across different experiments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "shao_manorm:_2012"

\end_inset

.
 MANorm uses the overlapping peaks called on individual experiments from
 a peak caller such as MACS as inputs and then normalizes all reads by the
 linear model.
 Then, the peak calls are adjusted using a Bayesian Poisson.
 MANorm is conceptually similar to a LOESS (locally weighted scatterplot
 smoothing) normalization which has been applied to other normalizations
 such as DIME 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taslim_comparative_2009"

\end_inset

.
 MANorm treats overlapping peaks similar to the locally weighted points
 from LOESS, however LOESS is a non-linear correction, and MANorm is linear.
 
\end_layout

