Normalization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The comparison of the read scores shows some clear differences across different
 conditions (strains), but is some evidence of bias and noise in the data.
 If the read depth is not equal for the experiments it results then we would
 expect the slope to be linearly offset across the entire experiment.
 Some early studies showed that there were peaks in the input control DNA
 proximal to promoter regions which is a source of bias.
 Others have shown mappability and GC content as a model of bias is important
 for comparing ChIP to input 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "liang_detecting_2011"

\end_inset

.
 These results shows evidence for a possible non-linear interaction of read-dept
h and transcription factor binding site coverage.
 We explored several options for normalizing the data including background
 subtraction, scaling, NormDiff 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zheng_genetic_2010"

\end_inset

, MANorm and DIME for linear and non-linear correction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Random 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and bias can exist in high throughput experiments so a good model of ChIP-seq
 data will be able to account for these features.
 The background 'noise' from ChIP-seq can be the result from non-regulatory
 interactions with the DNA, and a common approach is to subtract this background.
 MACS uses the rate of the background interactions from input control as
 a bar.
 To subtract the noise the median of the background data can be subtracted
 away.
 This constant subtraction accounts for noise but not necessarily bias.
 Also, it changes the original scale and returns values that are less than
 zero.
 One method for dealing with this is to simply assign zero to all less than
 zero values.
 
\end_layout

